**Executive Summary — 990 Eliminator Engineering Preview Configurator (EPC)**

![][image1]

Figure 1: EPC Visual Flow Builder Preview

The 990 Eliminator Engineering Preview Configurator (EPC) is a browser-based tool concept designed to accelerate the hydraulic design process for Spudnik’s 990 Eliminator line. The goal is to create a structured, interactive environment where engineers can build, visualize, and evaluate hydraulic systems using standardized power units, functions, and assemblies — all within a rule-driven flowchart that automatically generates an early-stage Bill of Materials (BOM).

This tool serves as a proof of concept for broader digital standardization across Spudnik’s Fluid Power division.

Purpose  
To give Fluid Power Engineers the ability to rapidly configure and validate rough-draft hydraulic systems for custom 990 Eliminators. The EPC aims to help engineers:

\- Reduce time spent searching through schematics and drawings.  
\- Reuse existing validated designs.  
\- Maintain standardization while preserving room for custom engineering.

Primary Users  
\- Fluid Power Engineering Team (internal use only, led by Daniel Cornia).  
  \- Intended for use during early machine design and validation.  
  \- Provides a reference framework for Controls and Manufacturing once validated.

Scope — Version 1  
Domain: Hydraulics-only (Power Units, Pumps, Valves, Flow Dividers, Cylinders, Load Holding, and related assemblies).

Deliverables:  
1\. Standalone browser-based configurator (HTML/CSS/JavaScript).  
2\. Visual flowchart builder:  
   \- Supports multiple power units and pumps.  
   \- Each pump maintains an independent buildable branch.  
   \- Interactive node placement and deletion.  
3\. Rule-based evaluation engine:  
   \- Determines recommended assemblies based on function selections.  
   \- Applies standard logic for flow dividers, PO checks, load holding, and valve configurations.  
   \- Includes “reason for inclusion” text for auditability.  
4\. Pump capacity validation:  
   \- Flags when branch demand exceeds pump flow or pressure.  
5\. Output formats:  
   \- BOM Preview (in-browser).  
   \- Export to Excel and JSON (for import/export of build data).

Out of Scope (v1)  
\- Electrical or pneumatic systems.  
\- Integration with Automation Studio, NX, or Teamcenter (planned for later versions).  
\- Commercial or quoting applications.  
  \- While the EPC could eventually support custom quoting or labor reduction analysis by leveraging standardized configurations, Version 1 will focus strictly on engineering feasibility and technical validation.

Future Vision  
Later versions may:  
\- Integrate directly with Automation Studio for schematic synchronization.  
\- Provide Excel-to-Teamcenter linkage for BOM population.  
\- Expand to include electrical validation (HP, voltage, and load calculations).  
\- Support custom quote generation for Sales Engineering to reduce manual labor while maintaining pricing accuracy.

Success Criteria  
Version 1 will be considered successful when:  
\- Engineers can fully build, visualize, and export a standard 990 hydraulic configuration without referencing paper schematics.  
\- The system consistently recommends accurate assemblies from the standard parts library.  
\- The exported Excel BOM provides a reliable foundation for final design review and potential downstream automation.

Project Approver:
